48    /**
49    * Implements a (generalized) LIBOR market model with generic covariance structure (lognormal, normal, displaced or stochastic volatility)
50    * with some drift approximation methods.
51    * <br><br>
52    * In its default case the class specifies a multi-factor LIBOR market model in its log-normal formulation, that is
53    * <i>L<sub>j</sub> = exp(Y<sub>j</sub>) </i> where
54    * \[
55    * dY_{j} = \mu_{j} dt + \lambda_{1,j} dW_{1} + \ldots + \lambda_{m,j} dW_{m}
56    * \]
57    * <br>
58    * The model uses an {@link net.finmath.montecarlo.interestrate.models.covariance.LIBORCovarianceModel} for the specification of
59    * <i>(&lambda;<sub>1,j</sub>,...,&lambda;<sub>m,j</sub>)</i> as a covariance model.
60    * See {@link net.finmath.montecarlo.model.ProcessModel} for details on the implemented interface
61    * <br><br>
62    * However, the class is more general:
63    * <ul>
64    * <li>
65    * The model may be log-normal or normal specification with a given local volatility.
66    * </li>
67    * <li>
68    * The class implements different measure(drift) / numeraire pairs: terminal measure and spot measure.
69    * </li>
70    * <li>
71    * The class allows to configure a discounting curve (e.g.&nbsp;for "OIS discounting") using a simple deterministic zero spread.
72    * In this case, the numeraire \( N(t) \) is adjusted by \( \exp( \int_0^t -\lambda(\tau) d\tau ) \).
73    * </li>
74    * </ul>
75    *
76    * <br>
77    * The class specifies a LIBOR market model, that is
78    * <i>L<sub>j</sub> = f(Y<sub>j</sub>) </i> where
79    * <ul>
80    * <li>
81    * <i>f</i> is <i>f(x) = exp(x)</i> (default, log-normal LIBOR Market Model) or
82    * </li>
83    * <li>
84    * <i>f</i> is <i>f(x) = x</i> (normal model, used if <code>property.set("stateSpace","NORMAL"))</code>
85    * </li>
86    * </ul>
87    * and
88    * <br>
89    * <i>dY<sub>j</sub> = &mu;<sub>j</sub> dt + &lambda;<sub>1,j</sub> dW<sub>1</sub> + ... + &lambda;<sub>m,j</sub> dW<sub>m</sub></i> <br>
90    * <br>
91    * see {@link net.finmath.montecarlo.model.ProcessModel} for details on the implemented interface.
92    * <br>
93    * The model uses an <code>AbstractLIBORCovarianceModel</code> as a covariance model.
94    * If the covariance model is of type <code>AbstractLIBORCovarianceModelParametric</code>
95    * a calibration to swaptions can be performed.
96    * <br>
97    * Note that &lambda; may still depend on <i>L</i>, hence generating a log-normal dynamic for <i>L</i> even
98    * if the stateSpace property has been set to NORMAL.
99    * <br>
100    *
101    * The map <code>properties</code> allows to configure the model. The following keys may be used:
102    * <ul>
103    * <li>
104    * <code>measure</code>: Possible values:
105    * <ul>
106    * <li>
107    * <code>SPOT</code>: Simulate under spot measure. In this case, the single curve numeraire
108    * is \( N(T_{i}) = \prod_{j=0}^{i-1} (1 + L(T_{j},T_{j+1};T_{j}) (T_{j+1}-T_{j})) \).
109    * </li>
110    * <li>
111    * <code>TERMINAL</code>: Simulate under terminal measure. In this case, the single curve numeraire
112    * is \( N(T_{i}) = P(T_{n};T_{i}) = \prod_{j=i}^{n-1} (1 + L(T_{j},T_{j+1};T_{i}) (T_{j+1}-T_{j}))^{-1} \).
113    * </li>
114    * </ul>
115    * </li>
116    * <li>
117    * <code>stateSpace</code>: Possible values:
118    * <ul>
119    * <li>
120    * <code>LOGNORMAL</code>: The state space transform is set to exp, i.e., <i>L = exp(Y)</i>. When the covariance model is deterministic, then this is the classical lognormal LIBOR market model. Note that the covariance model may still provide a local volatility function.
121    * </li>
122    * <li>
123    * <code>NORMAL</code>: The state space transform is set to identity, i.e., <i>L = Y</i>. When the covariance model is deterministic, then this is a normal LIBOR market model. Note that the covariance model may still provide a local volatility function.
124    * </li>
125    * </ul>
126    * </li>
127    * <li>
128    * <code>liborCap</code>: An optional <code>Double</code> value applied as a cap to the LIBOR rates.
129    * May be used to limit the simulated valued to prevent values attaining POSITIVE_INFINITY and
130    * numerical problems. To disable the cap, set <code>liborCap</code> to <code>Double.POSITIVE_INFINITY</code>.
131    * </li>
132    * </ul>
133    * <br>
134    * The main task of this class is to calculate the risk-neutral drift and the
135    * corresponding numeraire given the covariance model.
136    *
137    * The calibration of the covariance structure is not part of this class. For the calibration
138    * of parametric models of the instantaneous covariance see
139    * {@link net.finmath.montecarlo.interestrate.models.covariance.AbstractLIBORCovarianceModelParametric#getCloneCalibrated(LIBORMarketModel, CalibrationProduct[], Map)}.
140    *
141    * @author Christian Fries
142    * @version 1.2
143    * @see net.finmath.montecarlo.process.MonteCarloProcess The interface for numerical schemes.
144    * @see net.finmath.montecarlo.model.ProcessModel The interface for models provinding parameters to numerical schemes.
145    * @see net.finmath.montecarlo.interestrate.models.covariance.AbstractLIBORCovarianceModel The abstract covariance model plug ins.
146    * @see net.finmath.montecarlo.interestrate.models.covariance.AbstractLIBORCovarianceModelParametric A parametic covariance model including a generic calibration algorithm.
147    */
